{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657736"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:33:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:33:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20645"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20645"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.1,0.25,0.65]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13521"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94177"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13521"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20645"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77277"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10955"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11712"},{"type":"tags","id":"12533"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32292"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94177"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute inflammation is a protective response that can potentially cause tissue damage if not properly regulated. The body employs various mechanisms to ensure that inflammation resolves appropriately once it has served its purpose.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a mechanism that actively terminates the acute inflammatory response?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prolonged survival of neutrophils in inflamed tissues","Suppression of cholinergic neural impulses","Increased production of leukotrienes from arachidonic acid","Inhibition of transforming growth factor-\u03b2 release from macrophages","Switch from pro-inflammatory leukotrienes to anti-inflammatory lipoxins"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is the \u003Cstrong\u003Eswitch from pro-inflammatory leukotrienes to anti-inflammatory lipoxins\u003C/strong\u003E. This represents an active termination mechanism where the metabolism of arachidonic acid shifts from producing pro-inflammatory mediators (leukotrienes) to anti-inflammatory mediators (lipoxins), helping to resolve inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlonged survival of neutrophils in inflamed tissues\u003C/strong\u003E - Neutrophils have short half-lives in tissues and undergo apoptosis within hours after leaving the bloodstream. Their rapid clearance helps terminate inflammation rather than prolonging it.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuppression of cholinergic neural impulses\u003C/strong\u003E - Cholinergic neural impulses actually help terminate inflammation by inhibiting tumour necrosis factor production in macrophages. Suppressing these impulses would promote continued inflammation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased production of leukotrienes from arachidonic acid\u003C/strong\u003E - Leukotrienes are pro-inflammatory mediators that promote inflammation rather than terminate it.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of transforming growth factor-\u03b2 release from macrophages\u003C/strong\u003E - Transforming growth factor-\u03b2 (TGF-\u03b2) is an anti-inflammatory cytokine released from macrophages that helps terminate inflammation. Its inhibition would prolong rather than resolve inflammation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther mechanisms that help terminate acute inflammation include the short half-lives of inflammatory mediators, neutrophil apoptosis, and the release of anti-inflammatory cytokines like TGF-\u03b2 and interleukin-10 from macrophages and other cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute inflammation is self-limiting due to the short half-lives of inflammatory mediators and neutrophils.","Active termination mechanisms include the switch from pro-inflammatory leukotrienes to anti-inflammatory lipoxins.","Anti-inflammatory cytokines like transforming growth factor-\u03b2 and interleukin-10 help terminate the inflammatory response.","Neural mechanisms such as cholinergic discharge can inhibit tumour necrosis factor production in macrophages."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 85"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77277"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20645"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77277"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-23T13:17:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-23T13:19:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13521"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94177"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10955"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Acute inflammation